{{Infobox settlement |name=Luninets |native_name = Лунінец |nickname = |image_skyline =Луненец - panoramio (6).jpg |image_size = |image_caption = |image_flag =Flag of Łuniniec.svg |image_seal =Coat of Arms of Łuniniec, Belarus.svg |image_map = |map_caption = |pushpin_map=Belarus |subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]] |subdivision_name = {{flag|Belarus}} |subdivision_type1=[[Region]] |subdivision_name1=[[Brest Voblast|Brest Region]] |subdivision_type2=[[District]] |subdivision_name2=[[Luninets Raion]] |leader_title = |leader_name = |established_title = Mentioned |established_date = 1449 |area_magnitude = |area_total_km2 = 55 |area_land_km2 = |area_water_km2 = |population_as_of = 2009 |population_footnotes = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-43&srt=npan&col=abcdefghinoq&msz=1500&pt=c&va=&srt=pnan |title=World Gazetteer |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130111110701/http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-43&srt=npan&col=abcdefghinoq&msz=1500&pt=c&va=&srt=pnan |archivedate=January 11, 2013 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> |population_total =23608 |population_metro = |population_density_km2 = auto |timezone = [[Eastern European Time|EET]] |utc_offset = +2 |timezone_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]] |utc_offset_DST = +3 |coordinates = {{coord|52|15|N|26|48|E|region:BY|display=inline}} |elevation_m = |postal_code_type = Postal code |postal_code = 225642-225644 |area_code = +375 1647 |blank_name = License plate |blank_info = 1 |website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20130106141108/http://www.luninets.brest.by/ Official website] {{ref-ru}} |footnotes = }} '''Luninets''' ({{lang-be|Лунінец}}, {{lang-ru|Лунине́ц}},<ref>D.E. Rosental, ''Slovar' udarenii dlya rabotnikov radio i televideniya'' (Moscow, 1984), p. 640.</ref> {{lang-pl|Łuniniec}}, {{lang-lt|Luninecas}}, {{lang-yi|לונינייץ|Luninitz}} [[BGN/PCGN romanization of Belarusian|BGN/PCGN romanization]]: ''Luninyets'') is a town and administrative centre for the Luninets district in [[Brest Province]], [[Belarus]], before which it was in [[Poland]] (1540–1793, 1920–1939) and [[Russia]] and the [[Soviet Union]] (1793–1920, 1939–1941, 1944–1991). It has a population of some 24,000, and is immediately east of the [[Pinsk|Pinsk district]] within Brest. It was home to [[Luninets (air base)|Luninets air base]] during the [[Cold War]].
== History == Luninets is said to be mentioned in print sources dating to 1540. It was part of the [[Pinsk]] region which was under Polish rule between the 16th and 18th centuries but fell to [[Russia]] in 1793 in the [[Partitions of Poland|Second Partition of Poland]]. In 1888, while under Russian sovereignty, a railway junction was built in Luninets, linking it by rail to [[Warsaw]], [[Rivne]], [[Vilna]] and [[Homel]], and a proper railroad station was added in 1905.
Luninets became part of [[Poland]] in 1920 following the [[Polish-Soviet War]], but nineteen years later was incorporated back into the [[Soviet Union]] in 1939, and, with the exception of occupation by [[Nazi Germany]] from 10 July 1941 to 10 July 1944, remained part of the Soviet Union until 1991, at which time sovereignty ceded to the Republic of [[Belarus]].
The Jewish population was important in the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sztetl.org.pl/en/article/luniniec/5,history/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-05-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604033337/http://www.sztetl.org.pl/en/article/luniniec/5,history/ |archivedate=2016-06-04 |df= }}</ref> From 1941 to 1943, 4 000 Jews were murdered in mass executions perpetrated by an [[Einsatzgruppe]].<ref>http://moreshet.pl/he/node/1109</ref><ref>http://holocaustcontroversies.blogspot.fr/2006/05/mass-graves-in-polesie.html</ref><ref>http://www.yadvashem.org/yv/he/research/ghettos_encyclopedia/ghetto_details.asp?cid=525#!prettyPhoto</ref>
