{{Korean shamanism}}
[[File:Village devil posts.jpg|thumb|"Village devil posts", ''[[jangseung]]'' as described in ''[[:wikisource:The passing of Korea|The passing of Korea]]'' (1906) by the American Protestant missionary Homer Bezaleel Hulbert.]]
The '''movement to overthrow the worship of gods''' ([[Hangul]]: 미신 타파 운동 ''misin tapa undong''), also described as '''movement to overthrow superstition''', as 미신 ''misin'' is also translated after the movement, was a series of waves of [[demonisation]] and attempted violent uprooting of [[Korean shamanism]] and folk religion that took place in the period between the late 19th century and the 1980s.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|pp=4–7}} In modern [[Korean language]], ''misin'' has the meaning of "illusory" or "false spiritual beliefs", and implies that gods and ancestors do not exist. This term was adopted from [[Japanese language|Japanese]] in the late 19th century, and largely emphasised by [[Christian missionaries]] to target Korean indigenous religion.{{sfnb|Connor|Samuel|2001|pp=28–29}}

Waves of ''misin tapa undong'' started in the 1890s with the rise of influence of [[Protestantism|Protestant]] preachers in [[Korea]],{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|pp=4–7}} and culminated during the [[New Community Movement]] of the 20th century, in [[South Korea]]. These movements destroyed most of the indigenous cults and shrines of folk religion, which were largely replaced by [[Christianity]].{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=10}}

==Waves==
===Late Joseon (1890s)===
{{See also|Joseon}}
[[Protestantism]] sunk deep roots in Korea in the 1890s, establishing a network of schools and hospitals.{{sfnb|Connor|Samuel|2001|p=29}} Protestant missionaries labeled indigenous religious practices and shamans as "devil worship".{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|pp=4–7}} The missionaries led campaigns for the burning of idols, [[ancestral tablet]]s, shamans' tools and clothes, and shrines. According to missionary reports, they were "destroyed as were the books in Ephesus".{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=5}} The missionaries also circulated stories about shamans who had converted to Christianity becoming themselves advocates of the destruction of the indigenous religion.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=5}} The exorcistic struggle between a shaman and a Christian was made into a literary motif with Kim Tongni's colonial-period novella ''Portrait of a Shaman''.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=6}}

Missionaries found allies among Korean intellectuals in the final years of the [[Joseon]] kingdom. Together, they produced ''The Independent'' (''Tongnip Sinmun''), the first newspaper published in [[Korean language]].{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=7}}{{sfnb|Connor|Samuel|2001|p=29}} The newspaper promoted iconoclasm and addressed government officials on the necessity to eradicate the indigenous religion.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=7}}

In 1896, the police began to arrest shamans, destroy shrines and burn ritual tools. These events were acclaimed by ''The Independent''.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=8}} At one point, the newspaper even came to criticise [[Korean Buddhism|Buddhist monks]].{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=8}}

===Japanese occupation (1910–1945)===
{{See also|Korea under Japanese rule}}
Campaigns against Korean indigenous religious traditions also accompanied [[Japan]]'s annexation of the Korean peninsula. The Japanese had already equated secularisation with modernity in their own country.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=8}} The colonial police harassed and sometimes arrested shamans, though official policies against Korean shamanism were neither monolithic nor consistent.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=8}}

Following the rhetoric of ''The Independent'' of the foregoing generation, the colonial government portrayed the indigenous religion and the shamans as irrational and wasteful, adding the notion that they were also unhygienic.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=9}} Urban people adopted this rhetoric, seeking to distinguish themselves from their own rural origins.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=9}} Migrants to the cities rejected ''[[gut (ritual)|gut]]'' healing and traditional medicine.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=9}}

This paradigm would have become central to the projects for countryside development enacted in the independent [[South Korea]].{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=10}}

===Yi Seungman's government (1948–1960)===
Under [[Yi Seungman]]'s government, shamans were routinely harassed and arrested by the police.{{sfnb|Connor|Samuel|2001|p=31}} Protestants in [[Jeju Island]] led a "campaign against gods", through which they tried to exterminate Jeju's religious tradition and its pantheon of 18,000 deities.

===New Community Movement (1970s)===
{{See also|New Community Movement}}
In the 1970s, the president [[Park Chung-hee]] started the [[New Community Movement]] (''Saemaul Undong''), a mass mobilisation intended to transform rural society in both form and spirit.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=10}} Local communities were involved in a variety of public works.{{sfnb|Connor|Samuel|2001|p=28}}

Under the banner of such reform, a formal "Movement to Overthrow Superstition" (''Misin Tapa Undong'') was started. With official encouragement, police and local leaders suppressed ''gut'' rites and local cults.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=10}} They poured gasoline on village shrines and torched them, destroyed sacred trees, totem poles, and cairns, raided ''gut'' and arrested shamans.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=10}}{{sfnb|Connor|Samuel|2001|p=28}} Contemporary commenters criticise the movement for having damaged the indigenous religious tradition and having caused much of the South Korean population to adopt the foreign Christian religion.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=10}}

==Legacy==
In the aftermath of the wave of "anti-superstition movements", Korean indigenous religion was severely weakened. Since the 1980s, however, traditional religion and shamanism have experienced a revival in [[South Korea]].{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=10}} Since the 1990s, shamans started to be regarded as "bearers of culture".{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|p=22}} Today, Korean shamanism is recognised as a legitimate "religion" in South Korea, and there is widespread acknowledgement of "Muism" or "Sindo"—how shamanism is called—as the natural religion of the Koreans.{{sfnb|Kendall|2010|pp=29–30}}

