<!-- {{Otheruses4|Pahoran, the son of Nephihah|his son with the same name|Pahoran, son of Pahoran}}-->
'''Pahoran''' ({{IPAc-en|p|ə|ˈ|h|ɔr|ən}}),<ref>[http://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation?lang=eng LDS.org: "Book of Mormon Pronunciation Guide"] (retrieved 2012-02-25), "pa-hōr´un"</ref> in the [[Book of Mormon]], was the third chief judge of the Nephites, who inherited the position from his father [[List of Book of Mormon people#N|Nephihah]] in about 67 BC, in the 24th year of the judges  ({{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=50|verse=39|range=-40}}).

Soon after his appointment, he was opposed by the king-men, who wanted to dethrone the chief judge and replace him with a king. Supporting the chief judge and the current order were the "freemen". The people voted, and the freemen won ({{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51|verse=2|range=-7}}). The king-men were unwilling to defend their country against the attacks from [[Amalickiah]], which angered [[Captain Moroni|Moroni]]. Moroni requested Pahoran to give him the right to [[conscript]] the king-men or to have them executed for treason. Pahoran approved the request ({{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51|verse=13|range=-16}}).

Several years later, Moroni writes to Pahoran to request reinforcements but with no success. Moroni complained to Pahoran and questioned his loyalty to his country. Pahoran responded that the capital, [[Zarahemla]], was controlled by the king-men and that he had been exiled. He assures Moroni that he is not a traitor but wants only to preserve the liberty of his people ({{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=59|verse=3}},{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=60||nobook=}},{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=61||nobook=}}). Moroni and Pahoran gathered an army against [[Pachus]], the leader of the king-men. Pachus was slain, the king-men are executed, and Pahoran was restored to the judgement seat. Moroni and Pahoran work to drive the Lamanites from their land ({{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=62}}).

Finally, in around 53 BC, in the 39th year of the judgea, Pahoran dies, apparently while still the chief-judge ({{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Helaman|chapter=1|verse=1|range=-4}}).

