<!--Copied from King-men article merge-->

==King-men==
The '''king-men''' were a group of [[Nephites]] who sought to overthrow Judge Pahoran and install a king to rule the land. Some [[Nephites]] dissented from the current government and believed Chief-Judge Pahoran should change some laws, but Pahoran refused.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:2-3}}</ref> The dissenters, called king-men,<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:5}}</ref> then wanted a king to be appointed to govern instead of a chief-judge. However a public vote overruled them,<ref>[https://www.lds.org/manual/book-of-mormon-stories/chapter-33-king-men-versus-freemen?lang=eng&_r=1 ''Book of Mormon Stories'', (1997), Chapter 33: King-Men versus Freemen]</ref> and the rest of the people called themselves "freemen'' to distinguish their position and their desire to retain their religious freedoms.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:6}}</ref> Pahoran kept his position and there was no bloodshed.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:7}}</ref>

Meanwhile, [[Amalickiah]] gathered an army of [[Lamanites]] to attack the Nephites.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:9}}</ref> The freemen prepared to battle, but the king-men refused to defend their country.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:13}}</ref> [[Captain Moroni]], the leader of the Nephite armies, was angry from the king-men's stubbornness and petitioned Pahoran for legal authority to compel the king-men to defend their country or be executed.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:14-15}}</ref> By popular consent and the approval of Pahoran, Moroni and his armies quashed the king-men's rebellion, killing about 4000 men;<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:16-19}}</ref> the remainder of the king-men yielded to Moroni and took up arms in their country's defense.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=51:20}}</ref>

